<h1>From Charles Smith</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Dr Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Fort Loudoun Septr 7th 1758</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>your Letter of the first come safe to my hand, which I Sent the Inclosd Emediately to Hardwick &amp; Desired him at the same time to write you Every Particular.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
<p>I have kept an Exact Accout of your smiths work Done for the Publick &amp; Privet People,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> I have Wrote to the Governour for a small Supply, to Discharge some Deferent Accots Against the Contry &amp; with all to buoy some Necessaryes Shuch as nales, to Shingle the Barrax as I have most of my Timbers in.</p>
<p>The stone work of the south Bast End<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> is intirely Droping out &amp; without a Preaty Deal of Labour, the Whole must Fall before Winter as I have stone &amp; Lime if you think Proper I will Imploy a Mason to Rectefie the same an on as Reasonable Terms As Can be got.</p>
<p>you never wrote to me concerning Christopr Hensley, a Deserter
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-06-02-pb-0004">[4]</span>
from Your Regt from the Great Meadoes the Yr of 54 he is an Exstronary Good hand for Assisting about the Buildings at this Place as there is Absolute Necesity to keep some men Labouring.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0004" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0004-ptr">4</a></p>
<p>am I to make my Pay Roles for the Month of Augt concluding Davis Trottor Allsbery Bolton Hensley who has Recvd no Subsistance sence been here.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0005" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0005-ptr">5</a></p>
<p>The men is very Sickly here with Different Disorders I imployd a Doctr for some time but has Dischargd him by Reason his being Exstravegant &amp; noing but Little of Phisick.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0006" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0006-ptr">6</a></p>
<p>I Receivd your trunk by the waggons which I will take care to send Down by the firs[t] safe Oppertunity.</p>
<p>I was oblig. to keep Burris one Day after he came from Alexandrey, there being many Gentlemen at cort wanting to write to ther friends at camp &amp; withall to send the Last Papers up. I have kept a hors Burris Wrode Down here very Poor, which most People says he is yours,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0007" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0007-ptr">7</a> &amp; as Mr Hughs wants to send his Rideing horse Down I have sent one for Bagage for him.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0008" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0008-ptr">8</a></p>
<p>I Receivd a Deserter Yeasterday Name David Davis who belongd to Colo. Stephens Detachmt which I Shall send up by Lieut. King.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0009" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0009-ptr">9</a></p>
<p>I have sent you Eight Dozn Eggs &amp; 6 pounds of Allmonds, by Lieut. King which I hope will get safe to hand, if you should want any Particular Necessarys up by the convoy of waggons I hope you will make free of writeing to me, Mentioning the Particulars.</p>
<p>I Emagin you have heard of poor Colo. Spotsward Dying about Seven Days ago &amp; old Colo. Russell is Dead.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0010" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0010-ptr">10</a></p>
<p>by all Accot there is a worse Prospect of corn &amp; Tobacco as Ever has been in Virginia.</p>
<p>I have Inquired of Every one about your mare but can get no Account of her, it is talkt of by some People the man you bought her off Keeps her in Persession which I am Desired not to advertise her yet, &amp; to send a Private Per[s]on to his house I intend this Day to concult with Mr Sniggars &amp; see if I can get him to go up,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0011" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0011-ptr">11</a> I am informd a Mare you bough[t] of Capt. Lindseys Son is gone to her old walks on Spout Run this I Shall Inquire into.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0012" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0012-ptr">12</a></p>
<p>your Peeter is Extreamly ill I believe with the Plurisy; I have Hireed a Dutch smith for a few Days, untill he gets better.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0013" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0013-ptr">13</a></p>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-06-02-pb-0005">[5]</span>
<p>we have got the well 103 Feet Deep, but no likeliwhood of water Yet, I have no more to add, but Dr Sir Believe I am Your Friend &amp; most Obedt Hhble Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Chs Smith</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0001">1</a>
   
   <p>Neither <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0352" class="document">GWs letter to Smith of 1 Sept.</a> nor the letter enclosed in it to Christopher Hardwick has been found; but see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0364&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-05-02-0364-fn-0001#GEWN-02-05-02-0364-fn-0001" class="document">Hardwick to GW, 3 Sept., n.1</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>Smith wrote GW again on 12 Oct. about his blacksmiths account. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-06-02-0059&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-06-02-0059-fn-0004#GEWN-02-06-02-0059-fn-0004" class="document">note 4</a> of that document.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>Smith, who was charged with carrying on the construction of Fort Loudoun, wrote on 18 Sept. that he had employed a man to begin work on the south bastion of the fort, and he wrote again on 12 Oct. that he had hired two masons to help with the work.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0004">4</a>
   
   <p>Smith wrote GW about Christopher Hensley on <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0344" class="document">27 August</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>For the probable identification of Davis, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-06-02-0002&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0009#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0009" class="document">note 9</a>. Sgt. Richard Trotter, who enlisted in the Virginia Regiment in 1754, was in Capt. Henry Woodwards company. Smith wrote GW about Thomas (or Charles) Albery and Richard Bolton on 15 August.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0006">6</a>

   <p>For Smiths most recent return of the garrison at Fort Loudoun, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0344&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-05-02-0344-fn-0001#GEWN-02-05-02-0344-fn-0001" class="document">Smith to GW, 27 Aug., n.1</a>. He reported twenty-eight sick and twenty-two well.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0007-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0007">7</a>

   <p>Smith wrote GW in detail on <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-06-02-0025" class="document">18 Sept.</a> about the horse that Thomas Burris rode down to Winchester and Alexandria with GWs letters and then back to Winchester. In October Smith sent the horse up to GWs Bullskin plantation (<a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-06-02-0059" class="document">Smith to GW, 12 Oct.</a>).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0008-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0008">8</a>

   <p>William Hughes was a sergeant in Robert Stewarts company in the Virginia Regiment from November 1754 until June 1757 when he became adjutant of the regiment.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0009-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0009">9</a>

   <p>This seems to be the Davis that Smith refers to earlier in this letter (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-06-02-0002&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0005#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0005" class="document">note 5</a>), and he certainly is the David Davis that Smith writes about on 18 September. In 1757 there were at least two David Davises in the Virginia Regiment: one, drafted in Bedford County in 1756, was in Joshua Lewiss company; the other, drafted in 1755 at Winchester, was in Robert Stewarts company. A David Davis was reported in Capt. Thomas Bullitts company in October 1758. John King was made a lieutenant in GWs regiment in September 1755.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0010-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0010">10</a>

   <p>John Spotswood of Spotsylvania County was the son of Gov. Alexander Spotswood (16761740) and the brother of Lt. Robert Spotswood of GWs regiment who was killed in June 1757 in a skirmish with the Indians. Colonel Russell is probably Col. William Russell of Culpeper County.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0011-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0011">11</a>

   <p>For details about this black mare that had strayed, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0364&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-05-02-0364-fn-0004#GEWN-02-05-02-0364-fn-0004" class="document">Christopher Hardwick to GW, 3 Sept., n.4</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-06-02-0059" class="document">Smith to GW, 12 October</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0012-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0012">12</a>

   <p>For details about the lost bay mare, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0364&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-05-02-0364-fn-0004#GEWN-02-05-02-0364-fn-0004" class="document">Christopher Hardwick to GW, 3 Sept., n.4</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-06-02-0059" class="document">Smith to GW, 12 October</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0013-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0013">13</a>

   <p>The slave Peter recovered and was serving as GWs blacksmith at Mount Vernon in 1760.</p>

</div>
</div>
